1:# Recipe 6.2: Utilization Pattern Segmentation (Python Example)
9:## Setup
26:## Config and Constants
45:# Structured logging. Never log member IDs or PHI in production.
49:# Retry config for AWS API calls.
52:# boto3 clients (module-level for Lambda container reuse).
56:# --- Feature Configuration ---
58:# These are the utilization dimensions we cluster on.
59:# Each feature captures a different aspect of how a member uses healthcare.
60:# The choice of features is the single most important design decision in this
61:# pipeline. Get these wrong and your segments will be meaningless.
73:# --- Clustering Configuration ---
75:# Number of segments to discover. 4-6 is typical for utilization segmentation.
76:# Too few and you lose actionable distinctions. Too many and care managers
77:# can't design distinct interventions for each segment.
80:# Random seed for reproducibility. KMeans initialization is stochastic;
81:# setting this ensures you get the same segments on repeated runs with
82:# the same data. Change it when you want to explore alternative solutions.
85:# --- Segment Labels ---
86:# After clustering, we assign human-readable labels based on the centroid
87:# characteristics. These are the labels population health teams actually use.
88:# The mapping from cluster number to label happens in the interpretation step.
